      "content": "My apologies for the confusion. Let's get straight to the math then. The formula to calculate the interest for a single month on a student loan is:\n\nInterest for the month = (Principal Balance) x (Monthly Interest Rate)\n\nFirst, you need to convert the annual interest rate to a monthly rate by dividing it by 12. So, if your annual interest rate is 5%, the monthly interest rate would be 5% / 12 = 0.4167%.\n\nNow, let's apply this to your example. If you have a principal balance of $30,000 and a monthly interest rate of 0.4167%, the interest for the month would be:\n\nInterest for the month = $30,000 x 0.004167 = $125\n\nSo, for that month, the interest added to your balance would be $125. This means your new balance would be $30,125. Remember, this interest is calculated on the remaining balance, so as you make payments, the interest will decrease, and you'll be paying down the principal more effectively. Keep at it, and you'll see the goblin's influence diminish over time.",
